      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "HCHO"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "A"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "For a carbonyl group to give Cannizzaro reaction, it should not have an $$\\alpha$$-hydrogen atom. Among the given compound Ne<sub>3</sub>CCHO, C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>CHO and HCHO respond to Cannizzaro reaction but Cl<sub>3</sub>CCHO do not due to the following reason.<br><br><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1m5alu97k/aaeaadbb-6cd5-4615-a5d1-0345340ad850/bc169200-c66f-11ef-95a8-2787fde10bdd/file-jaoe38c1m5alu97l.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1m5alu97k/aaeaadbb-6cd5-4615-a5d1-0345340ad850/bc169200-c66f-11ef-95a8-2787fde10bdd/file-jaoe38c1m5alu97l.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"WB JEE 2016 Chemistry - Aldehyde and Ketone Question 5 English Explanation\"><br><br>When hydroxyl group attacks the carbonyl group a tetrahedral intermediate forms. The tetrahedral intermediate will revert to a carbonyl compound by expelling the best leaving group. The $$\\mathop C\\limits^\\Theta  C{l_3}$$ carbonium is resonance stabilised therefore it is better leaving group than $$\\overline O H$$. These initial products exchange a proton to give ion of carboxylic acid and trichloromethane (CHCl<sub>3</sub>).",
